Exercise 2.5

Given stuff:

pmold = 0.18 # P(infected)
# P(tree | infected)
tree.inf <- c(0.15, 0.8, 0.05)
names(tree.inf) <- c("elm", "maple", "other")
# P(tree | uninfected)
tree.un <- c(0.2,0.1,0.7)
names(tree.un) <- c("elm", "maple", "other")
# a. prior P(mold) = 
pmolda = 0.18 
# P(maple) = P(maple & infected) + P(maple & uninfected)
# = P(maple | infected) * P(infected) + P(maple | uninfected) * P(uninfected)
pmaple  = tree.inf["maple"]*(pmold)  + tree.un["maple"]*(1-pmold)
# P(mold | maple) = P(mold & maple)/pmaple
ppost <- tree.inf["maple"]*(pmold)/pmaple

Exercise 2.11 (Internship)

support = c(0.3,0.4, 0.5)
prior = c(0.25, 0.60,   0.15)
# a. Y|pi ~ Binomial(n=6, p = pi)
# b. P(y = 4 | pi = 0.3)
dbinom(4, size = 6, prob = 0.3)
## [1] 0.059535
# c. to the the posterior we need the likelihood
like <- dbinom(4, size = 6, prob = support)

posterior = prior*like
posterior  = posterior/sum(posterior) # normalize
plot(support, posterior, type = "h", col = 2)

Chapter 3: The Beta-Binomial Bayesian Model

Exercise 3.1 (Tune your Beta prior: Take I)

# part a. 
# 0.4 = a/(a+b)
# -->  0.4*a + 0.4*b = a
# --> 0.4*b = 0.6*a
# --> b = 1.5*a


# based on the lanuage in the chapted "For example, the values of a  
# Beta(5,5) variable pi tend to deviate from their mean of 0.5 by 0.151"
# I think mayb the authors were trying to get at values s.t the sd = 0.2
# In that case, your hyperparameters would be a = 2; b = 3

## using equations (4) and (5) from lecture 3...
mu = 0.4 # center at 0.4
sig = 0.2
a = ((1-mu)/sig^2 - 1/mu)*mu^2
b = a*(1/mu - 1)

# mean:
a/(a+b) # centered at 0.4
## [1] 0.4
# sd:
sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1))) # 0.2
## [1] 0.2
# (Extra) In addition you could look at the 95% central credible intervals
# although none of them line up with 0.2-0.6 
alphas <- seq(0.5, 10, 0.5)
for (i in 1:length(alphas)){
  a = alphas[i]
  b = 1.5*alphas[i]
  CI = qbeta(c(0.025, 1-0.025), a, b)
  print(c(CI, a, b))
}

Exercise 3.3 (It’s OK to admit you don’t know)

# a Beta(1,1) AKA Unif(0,1) would fit the bill
a = 1; b = 1
# mean (eq can be found on Wikipedia)
a/(a+b) # 0.5
## [1] 0.5
# sd (eq can be found on Wikipedia)
sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  # 0.2886751
## [1] 0.2886751
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col = 1)


# smaller sd (use larger a/b)
a = 5; b = 5 # just one example
sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  # 0.1507557
## [1] 0.1507557
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col =2 ,add = TRUE)


# larger sd (use smaller a/b)
a = 0.5; b = 0.5 # just one example
sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  # 0.3535534
## [1] 0.3535534
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col = 3, add = TRUE)

legend("top", legend = c("Beta(1,1)", "Beta(5,5)", "Beta(0.5,0.5)"), col = 1:3, lty = 1)

alphas = c(0.5, 1, 2, 6, 6, 0.5)
betas = c(0.5, 1, 2, 6, 2, 6)
n = length(alphas)
for (i in 1:n){
  a = alphas[i]
  b = betas[i]
  add2plot = ifelse(i == 1, FALSE, TRUE)
  curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col=i, add = add2plot)
  print(paste(" with alpha =", a, "and beta = ", b, "--------------"))
  print(paste("mean = ", a/(a+b)))
  print(paste("mode = ", (a-1)/(a+b-2)))
  print(paste("sd = ", sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  ))
}

Exercise 3.9 (Interpreting priors)

# North Dakota Beta(8,2) prior. 
a = 8; b = 2
print(paste("mean = ", a/(a+b)))
## [1] "mean =  0.8"
print(paste("mode = ", (a-1)/(a+b-2)))
## [1] "mode =  0.875"
print(paste("sd = ", sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  ))
## [1] "sd =  0.120604537831105"
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col=1)

# Louisiana Beta(1,20) prior.
a = 1; b = 20
print(paste("mean = ", a/(a+b)))
## [1] "mean =  0.0476190476190476"
print(paste("mode = ", (a-1)/(a+b-2)))
## [1] "mode =  0"
print(paste("sd = ", sqrt((a*b)/((a+b)^2*(a+b+1)))  ))
## [1] "sd =  0.0454029804402663"
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), col=2, add = add2plot)

legend("top", legend = c("North Dakota", "Louisiana"), col = 1:2, lty = 1)

# the person from North Dakota thinks the majority of  U.S. residents (mean = 0.8, mode = 0.875) prefer the term "pop" whereas Louisiana is quite confidence that a very low proportion of U.S. residents perfer the term "pop" (mean = 0.05, mode = 0).

Exercise 3.10 (Different priors, different posteriors)

# North Dakota Beta(8,2) prior. 
a = 8; b=2            # prior parameter values
y = 12; n=50          # number of success; number of Bernoulli trials
aa = a+y; bb = b+n-y  # posterior parameter values
aad = aa; bbd = bb
# plot the posterior:
curve(dbeta(x, shape1 = aa, shape2 = bb), xlab=expression(pi),
      lwd=2, col="turquoise2", ylab="", xlim=c(0,1), main="North Dakota")
# plot the prior:
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), lwd=2, col="dodgerblue4",lty=2, add=TRUE)
# plot the likelihood:
curve(dbeta(x, y+1, n-y+1), lwd= 2, col=2, lty =2 , add=TRUE)

prior.name <- paste("Beta(", a, ", ", b,") Prior",sep="")
post.name = paste("Beta(", aa, ", ", bb,") Posterior",sep="")
legend("topright", legend = c(prior.name, "Likelihood", post.name), 
       lwd=c(2,2,3), lty=c(2,2,1), col=c("dodgerblue4", "red", "turquoise2"))

summarize_beta_binomial(alpha = 8, beta = 2, y = 12, n = 50)
# Louisiana Beta(1,20) prior.
a = 1; b = 20         # prior parameter values
y = 12; n=50          # number of success; number of Bernoulli trials
aa = a+y; bb = b+n-y  # posterior parameter values
aal = aa; bbl = bb
# plot the posterior:
curve(dbeta(x, shape1 = aa, shape2 = bb), xlab=expression(pi),
      lwd=2, col="turquoise2", ylab="", xlim=c(0,1), main="Louisiana")
# plot the prior:
curve(dbeta(x, a, b), lwd=2, col="dodgerblue4",lty=2, add=TRUE)
# plot the likelihood:
curve(dbeta(x, y+1, n-y+1), lwd= 2, col=2, lty =2 , add=TRUE)

prior.name <- paste("Beta(", a, ", ", b,") Prior",sep="")
post.name = paste("Beta(", aa, ", ", bb,") Posterior",sep="")
legend("topright", legend = c(prior.name, "Likelihood", post.name), 
       lwd=c(2,2,3), lty=c(2,2,1), col=c("dodgerblue4", "red", "turquoise2"))

summarize_beta_binomial(alpha = 1, beta = 20, y = 12, n = 50)
curve(dbeta(x, shape1 = aal, shape2 = bbl), xlab=expression(pi), lty = 2,
      lwd=2, col="turquoise2", ylab="", xlim=c(0,1), main="Posterior Comparison")
curve(dbeta(x, shape1 = aad, shape2 = bbd), xlab=expression(pi), add=TRUE,
      lwd=2, col="turquoise2", ylab="", xlim=c(0,1), main="Posterior Comparison")

legend("topright", legend = c("North Dakota", " Lousianna"), 
       lty=1:2, col="turquoise2")

# in light of the data, Lousianna is swayed more towards believing a larger proportion of U.S. residents prefer the word "pop".  Conversely, North Dakota is swayed more towards believing a smaller proportion of U.S. residents prefer the word "pop" than she originally thought.

Exercise 3.18 (More Beta-Binomial)

  1. Patrick
plot_beta_binomial(alpha = 3, beta = 3, y = 30, n = 40)

summarize_beta_binomial(alpha = 3, beta = 3, y = 30, n = 40)
  1. Harold
plot_beta_binomial(alpha = 3, beta = 3, y = 15, n = 20)

summarize_beta_binomial(alpha = 3, beta = 3, y = 15, n = 20)
# while both of the towns had the same proportion of people attending the protest, Patricks data had more observations hence his likelihood high more strength in influencing the posterior as compared with Harolds.  Consequently, Harold's posterior is centered slightly lower than Patricks and has larger variance (since it is summarizing less information than Patrick's). To put another way, Patrick posterior can be thought of as summarizing 44 observation (the prior samples (3 + 3 -2) + actually samples n = 40). While Harold's is only summarizing 24 observations (the prior samples (3 + 3 -2) + actually samples n = 20)

Exercise 5.11 (Normal-Normal calculation)

Prof. Abebe

m = 80; s = 4       # hyperparmeters for prior
sig = 3             # known population standard deviation
xbar = 86 ; n = 32  # data 
# posterior parameters
mupost = m*sig^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2) + xbar*n*s^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2)
sigpost = sqrt(s^2*sig^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2))
plot_normal_normal(mean = 80, sd = 4, sigma = 3, y_bar = 86, n = 32)

summarize_normal_normal(mean = 80, sd = 4, sigma = 3, y_bar = 86, n = 32)

Exercise 5.12 (Control brains) I

Exercise 5.13 (Australia)

sig = 5
m = 30; # prior
# i'll set 10--50 within 2 sd of the prior mean:
# --> 2sd = 30-10 --> sd = 10
s = 10
data("weather_perth")
hist(weather_perth$temp3pm)

# appear slightly skewed right
m =30; s = 10       # hyperparmeters for prior
sig = 5             # known population standard deviation
xbar = mean(weather_perth$temp3pm) ; n = length(weather_perth$temp3pm)  # data 
# posterior parameters
mupost = m*sig^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2) + xbar*n*s^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2)
sigpost = sqrt(s^2*sig^2/(n*s^2 + sig^2))
print(paste("posterior mean:", mupost))
## [1] "posterior mean: 24.00239940015"
print(paste("posterior sd:", sigpost))
## [1] "posterior sd: 0.158094122478065"
summarize_normal_normal(mean = 30, sd = 10, sigma = 5, y_bar = xbar, n = n)
plot_normal_normal(mean = 30, sd = 10, sigma = 5, y_bar = xbar, n = n)

Exercise 5.19 (The Beta-Geometric model)

Bolstad

11.3

Assume population is Normal\((\mu, \sigma^2)\) where the standard deviation \(\sigma = 3\) is known. Sample:

data <- c(38.7, 40.4, 37.2, 36.6, 35.9, 34.7, 37.6, 35.1, 37.5, 35.6)

part a

Use a Normal\((30,10^2\)) prior for \(\mu\). Find the posterior distribution.

Recall thse results: \[\begin{align*} p(\mu) &\sim \mathcal N(m_0, s_0^2)\\ p(\mu \mid x) &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean \dfrac {\dfrac{m_0}{s_0^2} + \dfrac{n\overline{x}}{\sigma^2} } {\dfrac{1}{s_0^2}+ \dfrac{n}{\sigma^2}}, % posterior variance \dfrac{1}{\dfrac{1}{s_0^2} + \dfrac{n}{\sigma^2}} \right)\\ \end{align*}\] Alternatively letting \(a = 1/s_0^2\) and \(b=n/\sigma^2\) we get \[\begin{align*} p(\mu \mid x) &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean \mu_n= \dfrac{am_0+ b\overline{x}}{a +b} , % posterior variance \sigma^2_n= \dfrac{1}{a+b} \right) \end{align*}\] Let’s make a function to go from a normal prior (with parameters \(m_0\), \(s_0^2\)) and normal likelihood (with sufficient statistics \(\overline{x}\) and \(n\)) to a normal posterior (with parameters \(\mu_n\) and \(\sigma^2_n\) given above)

# m = prior mean
# s0 = prior standard deviation (NOT VARIANCE)
# sig = known population standard deviation (NOT VARIANCE)
# xbar = sample mean
# n = number of observations
# y = data vector (if available you don't need to pass xbar and n)
normalUpdate <- function(m0,s0,sig, xbar=NULL, n=NULL, y){
  if (is.null(xbar)){
    n <- length(y)
    xbar <- mean(y)
  }
  a = 1/s0^2
  b = n/(sig^2)
  mu = (a*m0 + b*xbar)/(a + b)
  var = 1/(a+b)
  return(list(mean=mu, var=var, sd=sqrt(var)))
}

Calculate the sufficient statistcs

posteriora <- normalUpdate(m0=30, s0=10, sig=3, y=data) # or..
posteriorb <- normalUpdate(m0=30, s0=10, sig=3, xbar=mean(data), n=length(data))
all.equal(posteriora, posteriorb)
## [1] TRUE

Hence the posterior distribution is: \[\begin{align*} p(\mu \mid x) &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 36.868 , % posterior variance 0.944 \right) & \text{using standard deviation}\\ \text{or} &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 36.868 , % posterior variance 0.892 \right) & \text{using variance}\\ \text{or} &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 36.868 , % posterior variance 1.121 \right) & \text{using precision}\\ \end{align*}\]

part a

data <- c(940, 1040, 910, 990)

Using the function above, calculate the posterior:

posterior <- normalUpdate(m0=1000, s0=200, sig=40, y=data)

Hence the posterior distribution is: \[\begin{align*} p(\mu \mid x) &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 970.3 , % posterior variance 19.901 \right) & \text{using standard deviation}\\ \text{or} &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 970.3 , % posterior variance 396.04 \right) & \text{using variance}\\ \text{or} &\sim \mathcal N\left( % posterior mean 970.3 , % posterior variance 0.003 \right) & \text{using precision}\\ \end{align*}\]

Find a 95% credible interval for \(\mu\)

c <- 0.95
alpha = 1 -c
qnorm(c(alpha/2, 1-alpha/2), posterior$mean, posterior$sd)
